<dl id="n43106e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n43" href="#n43106e">N43 (VI.B.35)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n43all.htm#n43106e"> 106(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Aramean splits in / Parsi (Zoroaster) / Hebrew (Judaism) / <font face="wake">+</font>ism (Syriac) / Mongolian (Buddhism) / Arabic (Islam)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The later alphabets&mdash;Parsi, Hebrew, Syriac, Mongolian, and Arabic&mdash;were at first local varieties of the Aramean. Owing to accidental circumstances they became the sacred scripts of the five great faiths of Asia&mdash;Zoroastrianism, Judaism, Christianity, Northern Buddhism, and Islam. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECSA2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECSA2"><cite title="source">The Story of the Alphabet</cite></a>, rev. ed. (1913) 208 [Greek Papyri]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
